name: Darryl Gutierrez
text: This is a museum in the private home of artist and poet (Maria) Howard Weeden. The cost is $5 and the tour is about an hour long. I found it to be a fascinating glimpse into not only Weeden's life and art, but also the early history of Huntsville and North Alabama. Like many private museums, Weeden house has had to branch out to make ends meet so they rent the place out as an event venue as well. This means that Lynn, their lone employee is stretched rather thin as tour guide, event coordinator, curator and hostess so you should make an appointment for the guided tour. Nevertheless, she was as gracious and informative a hostess as you could wish for. Word of caution- there are stairs so if you have mobility issues you may miss the upstairs part of the tour.

name: Ken Barnes
text:
Our wedding and reception was in the back yard of the Weeden House. We had lots of questions and requests, and their event/property manager was incredibly flexible and responsive. It was a magical event, and the Weeden House was a huge part of making it feel special.

Note: it's one of the few facilities in Huntsville that does weddings but allows you to bring your own alcoholic drinks. No forced catering!

text:
This place gets 5 stars because there are no apparent downsides that I've ever noticed. Easy to find, just a few minutes of hwy 280.

Truthfully speaking, I've never been inside the larger museum room and am not exactly sure what all it entails. This review is specific to this building being used as a party/event venue. I've been on 3 separate occasions now (2 holiday parties and a baby shower) and have always had a good time. You can setup the room however you'd like with tables, chairs, microphone, speakers etc. There's also kitchen space and easily accessible restrooms to take advantage of.

On this same side of the building where parties can be hosted, there's also a little bit of interactive museum stuff... fun!! Some cool pictures and historical information displays can be found throughout this room as well! Brick walls, high open ceilings and all the rustic decor makes this place feel unique, authentic and like any other event venue that you'll find in Birmingham (that I know of).

Info I could find out:
Museums, Galleries and Archives (Local and County Historical Societies, Museums, and Archives)

This historic train depot was built by the former Gulf, Mobile and Ohio Railroad in 1911 to replace a station built in 1870. The city acquired it in 1995 and was restored by a joint effort of the Northport Historic Preservation Commission and the Black Warrior Model Railroad Association. It opened as a model railroad museum in 1999. Amtrak offers passenger service twice daily and Norfolk Southern Railway maintains an office in the building.

text: Great historic home and property of General Joe Wheeler.  Contains all original furnishings and personal items owned by the Wheeler family. Guided tours are given every hour and mine was excellent. My guide was extremely knowledgeable and informative and was a wealth of information. Gift shop is on site. Admission was just $8 or $5 for seniors, active military, and less for children. I highly recommend visiting here, especially if you are interested in history and/or old houses.

name: Steve Thomas
text:
The two story brick house in the photographs is the Bankhead House and Heritage Center and it is located between 8th and 9th Avenues.   The white house was another Bankhead home, Sunset, but it is a private residence which is located about 10 blocks south of the other house, on 7th Avenue. The Bankhead House and Heritage Center, which was totally renovated a few years ago, and the Walker Community Foundation office which is located across the street from it are tremendous assets to the community.

Downtown Jasper has come out of the doldrums and is flourishing. It has several restaurants (Tex-Mex, New Orleans style food, casual, sushi, barbecue, etc.) and entertainment venues within blocks of the Walker County Courthouse (entertainment district). It is just a short drive from Interstate 22 to this area, plus the four lane on the north side of town has several restaurants of various varieties and several fast food restaurants.

text: Cute experience. We went with some friends and the staff was very helpful. You'll be able to spend about an hour here but not much more. Found it very interesting and our kids enjoyed dressing up like cattle ranchers.

text: This was the best experience for my children.  They learned so much and when they see things out, they can related it back to the museum. The staff was very friendly and even made suggestions for farms to visit to get hands on experience. The dress up area was so much fun. My daughter said she enjoyed trying on chaps...who knew. They have a kitchen that is so educational and of course the kids can relate when in public. Highly recommend this FREE museum to past the time. Kids can't wait to return.

name: Mg 0
text: Interesting place, even for those with no interest in ranching or cows. Well, let’s amend that : it helps to have some interest at least in cows as historical bovine varieties, or have children who like to play dress up as cattlemen, or to want to learn a bit about Alabama’s cattle and cotton history, or agriculture at large. It’s donation-based, so nothing lost, in any case.

name: Adam Levin
text: A free museum (donations accepted) that the kids will enjoy. They particularly liked the role playing area where they could dress up as cowgirls and cowboys. Educational for parents as well.

name: Shelley Hammerman
text: We came last week and had the best time!  Very fun for the kids and we enjoyed ourselves.  It's so cool how there are things you didn't realize came from a cow.  I nearly didn't give 5 stars because you allow people who aren't handicapped to park in your handicapped spot.  My son is handicapped and while we used one of the other spots I find it completely sad that someone was so blatantly disrespectful.  They could have parked one spot over and left it accessible so that we could easily unload and have access to the ramp. Please do better for your Handicapped visitors.

resp.text: Thank you for your review, Brandi.  We apologize that you didn't enjoy your visit to The MOOseum.    We are a non-profit trade association for the beef cattle industry.  Our goals is to give children as well as adults a glimpse into the states history of the industry.  While visiting children have the opportunity to dress up and pretend to be cowboys and cowgirls at the rodeo.  They are also able to explore and see things that some may have never had the chance to see like a full sized stuffed cow named Dusty.   We hope that you will give us another chance and come back to explore some more.  We have locals who visit regularly and learn something new each time they are here!

name: PhatDookie 420
text: It's free and weird. Easy to find at the intersection of 169 and highway 431 in Seale, AL. It is something to see and it is free. There is a slot to donate but it is completely optional. You can see most of the art and oddities from your vehicle but to see every thing you have to park and look thru the windows at different angles. If you are going to Panama City Beach Florida  or in that general direction for spring break or summer or whatever then you will pass by it anyways so why not stop and see some of the art and weirdness Seale, AL has to offer? Thank you for reading my review and I hope you enjoy your visit.
